  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a subtle yet powerful barrier that affects individuals when they fear their performance might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. Growing up in Naples with a father who held a PhD and a mother with only a lower secondary education, I witnessed firsthand how societal expectations can shape opportunities. My own journey as a non-binary person navigating a field that often assumes gender roles taught me that stereotype threat isn't just about numbers—it's about the quiet anxiety that lingers when you're aware of being judged. In my retired years, I've seen how this issue manifests in classrooms and labs, where students from underrepresented groups may avoid participating or feel their contributions are undervalued. Addressing it requires more than just awareness; it demands systemic changes that empower individuals to thrive without fear. I've seen it in my grandchildren, who are eager to study engineering but worry about fitting into a world that seems to expect them to 'be different.' We must create inclusive spaces where every person feels valued, not just for their potential but for who they are. This isn't just a matter of policy—it's about nurturing the next generation with confidence and respect.",
